import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    avg_income_by_region = data.groupby('region')['pct'].mean()
    avg_income_by_region.plot(kind='bar')
    
    plt.xlabel('Region')
    plt.ylabel('Average Income Range')
    plt.title('What is the average income range of households in each region?')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    top_5_states = data.nlargest(5, 'total')
    pivot_data = top_5_states.pivot(index='name', columns='group', values='pct')
    pivot_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
    
    plt.title("What is the income distribution of the top 5 states with the highest total number of households?", wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Filter data for the income range of $100,000 to $149,999
    income_range_data = data[data['group'] == '100000 to 149999']

    # Load US states shapefile
    us_states = gpd.read_file('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PublicaMundi/MappingAPI/master/data/geojson/us-states.json')

    # Merge income data with shapefile
    merged_data = us_states.set_index('name').join(income_range_data.set_index('name'))

    # Plot choropleth map
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    merged_data.plot(column='pct', cmap='coolwarm', linewidth=0.8, edgecolor='0.8', legend=True)
    plt.title("What is the percentage of households in the income range of $100,000 to $149,999 in each state?", wrap=True)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    grouped_data = data.groupby(['group'])['total'].sum().reset_index()
    grouped_data.sort_values('total', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    
    plt.bar(grouped_data['group'], grouped_data['total'])
    plt.xlabel('Income Range')
    plt.ylabel('Total Number of Households')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title('What is the distribution of total number of households across different income ranges?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
